abstract: BINGHAMTON, N.Y., June 10. -- The Rev. George Horton, a retired Presbyterian clergyman, was instantly killed while driving into his yard near Oxford yesterday. abstract: Dr. MARY PUTNAM JACOBI, who died on Sunday, was in many regards a notable woman. As a student, practitioner, and teacher of medicine she won real distinction and achieved honors quite beyond the ordinary. She was a woman of strong character and intellect, of acute, penetrating, and independent judgment, devoting remarkable mental gifts to high aims and performing substantial service with the utmost fidelity and energy.

abstract: Following the advice of a negro soapbox orator, some 500 negroes who were angry because a policeman had just arrested Helen Wright, colored, threatened to "put out of business" Policeman Mangin yesterday afternoon at Lenox Avenue and 133d Street. abstract: Speeding at fifty miles an hour, the Atlantic City Express, over the Central Railroad of New Jersey, was wrecked at 10:15 o'clock yesterday morning at Eatontown, N.J. abstract: The promise of the Atlantic Yacht Club to afford an interesting regatta in the first big races of the season was fulfilled yesterday afternoon. abstract: Sportsmen in France are becoming furious advocates of wireless telegraphy. It appears that after carefully watching for three years a kilometer's length of telegraph wire in a district not overpopulated with birds, an interested observer has proved that one and a half head of game, such as partridges, pheasants, quail, and so on, is impaled yearly on every wire of this length in France, which means a total all over the country of 40,000 annually.

abstract: LEXOX, Mass., June 16. -- Visitors to the Berkshires have now settled down to the full enjoyment of the Summer months and already several small entertainments have been given. abstract: CHRISTIANIA, June 17. -- Trondhjem, yesterday a city of fishers, to-day is a capital. Many of those who will participate in the coronation of King Haakon have already swelled the population, and others are crowding north by steamers and trains. abstract: I am an old man and reflect much on the past, and especially upon the losses common to humanity. abstract: WASHINGTON, June 22. -- Four two-base hits, bunched in the third and fourth innings, tell the story of the defeat of the Greater New Yorks by Washington. Orth, usually invincible against his former teammates, was hit safely in all but two innings.

abstract: An open air carnival held in Bayonne, N.J., several weeks ago raised $17,000 for the benefit of the City Hospital. Last night the Ministers' Association of that city adopted resolutions censuring the money raising methods practiced at the carnival. Particularly the association criticised the operation of a game called "bats," somewhat on the lines of roulette, which brought in hundreds of dollars' toward the total of $17,000.

abstract: BELMAR, N.J., June 23. -- Sojourners continue to arrive daily at the many hotels here. The Colorado-Atlantic and the Columbia opened to-day, so that now the hotels are all open. abstract: UNLESS the prognostication of the Italian Government goes wrong, there will be a heavy falling off in the emigration from Sicily to this country. In 1905 no fewer than 62,897 passports were issued for Sicilians coming to this country. So far this year, however, less than 18,000 passports have been issued for the same destination, while the main current has been diverted to Brazil, Argentina, Algeria, Tunis, Tripoli, and Egypt.

abstract: HONOLULU, June 24. -- The schooner yacht Lurline, representing the South Coast Yacht Club of California, finished first in the race from San Pedro to Hawaii last evening. She crossed the line at 7:31 o'clock, having been out a total of 12 days and 5 hours in making the passage of 2,700 miles. Her average daily speed was nearly 230 miles, while her highest day's run was 265 miles, on the second day out.

abstract: R.J. abstract: " Capt. Roman Simonson, United States Army," has resigned as commander of the Second Field Artillery at Fort Riley, Kan. The "hero of Peking" and the "victor of a thousand bloody skirmishes on the Western plains" quit soldiering, at least, yesterday morning. From this on -- he says so himself -- he is to be known as plain Mr. Simonson, bookkeeper, of 354 West Twenty-seventh Street.

abstract: WASHINGTON, June 27. -- The House conferrees on the Meat bill to-day took the Senate by the throat. They declared that there was no use conferring; that unless the Senate accepted its contention the subject should be abandoned. abstract: PATERSON, N.J., June 27. -- The Manchester Building and Loan Association, at a big meeting at Haledon, decided to-night to dissolve. It was thought by the officers that the shareholders would receive dollar for dollar of the money paid in, which practically wipes out all the profits made by the association for ten years. The association was wrecked by its President, William H. Belcher, and George W. Allee.
